Certainly! Below is a simple HTML template that creates a showcase app for games from the specified API. The app will display games in an iframe, switching between them every 5 seconds after fetching a list of games from the API.

Hereâ€™s how the code is structured:
1. HTML for the basic layout.
2. CSS for basic styling.
3. JavaScript to fetch games, select random ones, and switch them in the iframe.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Game Showcase</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #282c34;
            color: white;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        iframe {
            border: none;
            width: 80%;
            height: 80%;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <iframe id="game-frame" src="" allowfullscreen></iframe>

    <script>
        const iframe = document.getElementById('game-frame');
        let games = [];
        const switchInterval = 5000; // 5 seconds

        // Function to fetch games from the API
        async function fetchGames() {
            const responses = await Promise.all([1, 2, 3].map(page => 
                fetch(`https://games.h4ks.com/api/games?sort_by=date_added&page=${page}`).then(res => res.json())
            ));
            games = responses.flatMap(response => response.data);
            startShowcase();
        }

        // Function to start showcasing games
        function startShowcase() {
            if (games.length > 0) {
                setInterval(() => {
                    const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * games.length);
                    const game = games[randomIndex];
                    if (game && game.url) {
                        iframe.src = game.url;
                    }
                }, switchInterval);
            }
        }

        // Fetch games once the page loads
        window.onload = fetchGames;
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- The HTML structure includes an `<iframe>` to display the games.
- The CSS styles the body and the iframe to center the content and provides a dark background.
- The JavaScript fetches games from the API, combining responses from pages 1 to 3. Adjust the number of pages if needed.
- The game URL is extracted from the response and the iframe's source is updated every 5 seconds with a randomly selected game URL.

### Usage:
- Save the code to an HTML file (e.g., `games_showcase.html`).
- Open the file in a web browser, and it will start showcasing the games automatically.

Feel free to modify the page count or styles according to your needs!
